import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.dates as mdates
import numpy as np

# Load your dataset with proper date parsing
nifty50_data = pd.read_csv("data/Nifty_50_with_indicators_.csv", parse_dates=['Date'])

# Reverse the order of rows
nifty50_data = nifty50_data.iloc[::-1].reset_index(drop=True)

# Choose the column for which you want to calculate the moving average
column_name = "close"  # Adjusted column name to lowercase

arr = [60, 125, 250]

for i in range(3):
    # Define the window size for the moving average
    window_size = arr[i]  # Example: 10-day moving average

    # Calculate the moving average using rolling function
    moving_average = nifty50_data[column_name].rolling(window=window_size).mean()

    # Create a new column in your DataFrame to store the moving average values
    nifty50_data['Moving_Average'] = moving_average

    # Plot the original data and the moving average

    plt.plot(nifty50_data_reversed['Date'], nifty50_data_reversed['Moving_Average'], label=f'{window_size}-day Moving Average')
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Price')
    plt.title(f'Moving Average of {column_name.capitalize()} prices')  # Capitalize column name for title
    plt.legend()

    # Set ticks to show only years
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(mdates.YearLocator())
    plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_formatter(mdates.DateFormatter('%Y'))

    plt.xticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
    plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to prevent clipping of labels
    plt.show()

    # Create a new column in your DataFrame to store the moving skewness values
    nifty50_data['Moving_Skewness'] = moving_skewness

    # Plot the moving skewness
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))

#making new column to find Log_return
nifty50_data['Log_Returns'] = nifty50_data[column_name].pct_change().apply(lambda x: np.log(1 + x))

arr = [60, 125, 250]
for i in range(3):
    window_size = arr[i]
    # Calculate the moving skewness of the log returns using rolling function
    moving_skewness_log_returns = nifty50_data['Log_Returns'].rolling(window=window_size).skew()

    # Plot the moving skewness of the log returns
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.plot(nifty50_data['Date'], moving_skewness_log_returns, label=f'{window_size}-day Moving Skewness of Log Returns', color='orange')
    plt.xlabel('Date')
    plt.ylabel('Skewness')
    plt.title('Moving Skewness of Log Returns')
    plt.legend()
    plt.axhline(y=0, color='k', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.8)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)  # Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
    plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to prevent clipping of labels
    plt.show()
